        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">How was the Romanov family killed?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/romanovs-russian-aristocracy-16th-17th-century-history.jpg" alt="The Romanovs were high-ranking aristocrats in Russia during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>The Romanovs were high-ranking aristocrats in Russia during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. Credits: Mondadori/ Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> The Romanov family, Russia's last imperial dynasty, was executed on July 17, 1918, by Bolshevik revolutionaries. After months of exile in Yekaterinburg, Russia, the Bolsheviks executed Tsar Nicholas II, his wife Alexandra, and their five children. They were asked to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-jul-25-foundation-h1-13-line-up-for-a-photo" target="_blank">line up for a photo</a>, citing documentation purposes. At that moment, a firing squad entered and opened fire. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The reasons:</strong> The family was murdered to eliminate the threat of restoring the monarchy. Many Russians <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-jul-25-foundation-h1-14-hated-the-reign" target="_blank">hated the reign</a> of Nicholas II because of the tensions over his autocratic rule, his failure in the First World War, the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-jul-25-foundation-h1-15-bloody-sunday-massacre" target="_blank">Bloody Sunday massacre</a>, and the mismanagement of inflation. Lenin and other Bolshevik leaders saw the execution as a way to consolidate power. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The aftermath:</strong> Their bodies were broken into pieces and scattered in the woods. The Soviets <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-jul-25-foundation-h1-16-denied-killing" target="_blank">denied killing</a> the entire family initially. There were rumors sparked that one of the daughters, Anastasia, was still alive, which led to many false assertions from different women claiming to be the lost princess. 
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         In 1991, the remains of Nicholas II, Alexandra, and three of their children were identified. They were reburied in St. Petersburg in 1998. The Russian Orthodox Church made the family martyrs. The last two children's remains were found in 200, putting to rest the rumor of a surviving princess. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <i>Learn more about the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-jul-25-foundation-h1-17-romanov-family" target="_blank">Romanov family</a>.</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
